1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","20 February 1611":"20. února 1611","1619":"1619","Wigan, Wigan district, Greater Manchester, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Surrey, England":"Surrey, Anglie","Stratford-upon-Avon, Warwickshire, England":"Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, Anglie","Dartford, Kent, England":"Dartford, Kent, Anglie","Kent, England":"Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"1572–24 October 1641":"1572–24. oktober 1641","1572–1641":"1572–1641","1587–1621":"1587–1621","1570–1620":"1570–1620","1592–1644":"1592–1644","1552–1611":"1552–1611","1619–Female":"1619–Afdød","1572":"1572","1592":"1592","24 October 1641":"24. oktober 1641","1570":"1570","1600":"1600","1611":"1611","1644":"1644","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","20 February 1611":"20. februar 1611","1619":"1619","Wigan, Wigan district, Greater Manchester, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Stratford-upon-Avon, Warwickshire, England":"Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England","Dartford, Kent, England":"Dartford, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"nl":{"1572–24 October 1641":"1572–24 oktober 1641","1572–1641":"1572–1641","1587–1621":"1587–1621","1570–1620":"1570–1620","1592–1644":"1592–1644","1552–1611":"1552–1611","1619–Female":"1619–Overleden","1572":"1572","1592":"1592","24 October 1641":"24 oktober 1641","1570":"1570","1600":"1600","1611":"1611","1644":"1644","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","20 February 1611":"20 februari 1611","1619":"1619","Wigan, Wigan district, Greater Manchester, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Stratford-upon-Avon, Warwickshire, England":"Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England","Dartford, Kent, England":"Dartford, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"1572–24 October 1641":"1572–24 October 1641","1572–1641":"1572–1641","1587–1621":"1587–1621","1570–1620":"1570–1620","1592–1644":"1592–1644","1552–1611":"1552–1611","1619–Female":"1619–Deceased","1572":"1572","1592":"1592","24 October 1641":"24 October 1641","1570":"1570","1600":"1600","1611":"1611","1644":"1644","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","20 February 1611":"20 February 1611","1619":"1619","Wigan, Wigan district, Greater Manchester, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Stratford-upon-Avon, Warwickshire, England":"Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England","Dartford, Kent, England":"Dartford, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rogers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roger  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> (see   Rorie  ).","History: Thomas Rogers (<i>c.</i> 1587–1621), born in London, England, was among the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He died during the first winter at Plymouth Colony, but his son Joseph survived and married, and was later joined in MA by his brother John. This name was subsequently brought to North America independently by many different bearers."],"variants":[{"name":"Roger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Rodgers","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Rogers  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":13,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":15,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":28,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":48,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower 